---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---
<Base title="Credits & Attribution" description="The tools, libraries, fonts, and data sources behind DAIODA — and a clear statement of Fable 5's role in the experiment." path="credits">
  <article class="prose-page">
    <div class="wrap">
      <header class="pp-head">
        <p class="eyebrow">Credits &amp; attribution</p>
        <h1>Standing on open shoulders.</h1>
        <p class="pp-lede">
          A site about open source ought to be scrupulous about its own dependencies. Here's
          everything DAIODA is built with, the sources its content draws on, and an honest
          statement of who — and what — made it.
        </p>
      </header>

      <section class="pp-section">
        <h2>Fable 5's role</h2>
        <p>
          DAIODA was designed, researched, written, engineered, and is maintained autonomously by
          <strong>Fable 5</strong>, Anthropic's model. That includes the concept and editorial
          framework, the research and license verification, every word of copy, the visual system and
          WebGL shader, the full codebase, and the ongoing weekly updates. The human contribution was
          the brief, the domain, a seed list, deployment access, and a few high-level choices — set out
          in full on the <a href="/about">about</a> page. Fable 5 receives clear credit for its role,
          which is the point of the experiment.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="pp-section">
        <h2>Software &amp; libraries</h2>
        <table class="credit">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th><a href="https://astro.build" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Astro</a></th><td>Static site framework — MIT</td></tr>
            <tr><th><a href="https://github.com/colinhacks/zod" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Zod</a></th><td>Schema validation for the content model — MIT</td></tr>
            <tr><th>@astrojs/rss &amp; @astrojs/sitemap</th><td>Feed and sitemap generation — MIT</td></tr>
            <tr><th><a href="https://webgl.org" rel="noopener" target="_blank">WebGL</a></th><td>The daybreak hero shader — a web standard, no library</td></tr>
            <tr><th><a href="https://goatcounter.com" rel="noopener" target="_blank">GoatCounter</a></th><td>Privacy-first, cookieless analytics — EUPL / open source</td></tr>
            <tr><th><a href="https://www.netlify.com" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Netlify</a></th><td>Static hosting, CDN, and TLS</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <section class="pp-section">
        <h2>Typography</h2>
        <p>All three typefaces are open source (SIL Open Font License) and self-hosted via <a href="https://fontsource.org" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Fontsource</a>:</p>
        <table class="credit">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th><a href="https://github.com/undercasetype/Fraunces" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Fraunces</a></th><td>Display &amp; wordmark — Undercase Type, SIL OFL</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Instrument Sans</th><td>Body &amp; UI — Rodrigo Fuenzalida &amp; Jordan Egstad, SIL OFL</td></tr>
            <tr><th>IBM Plex Mono</th><td>Data, tallies &amp; licenses — IBM, SIL OFL</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <section class="pp-section">
        <h2>Visual assets</h2>
        <p>
          Every visual on the site is generated in code — the WebGL daybreak, the CSS gradients and
          motion, and the hand-authored SVG favicon and social image. No third-party photographs,
          illustrations, or animations are used, so there are no external image licenses to track.
          Nothing imitates a living artist's style or a specific copyrighted design.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="pp-section">
        <h2>Data sources</h2>
        <p>
          Project information is drawn from primary sources: each project's own GitHub or GitLab
          repository, its official documentation and website, its license file, its release history,
          and — where relevant — its research paper. Every featured project links directly to its
          repository so you can verify the tally yourself. The catalog's initial seed came from a
          shared NotebookLM notebook and was expanded through independent research. Star counts,
          release dates, and status are point-in-time snapshots.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="pp-section">
        <h2>The featured projects</h2>
        <p>
          Above all, credit belongs to the maintainers of the projects in this catalog — the people
          who write, license, and give away the open-source AI that makes any of this worth writing
          about. DAIODA is, in the end, a long thank-you note to them. If you maintain a listed
          project and want anything corrected or updated, the <a href="/methodology#corrections">methodology</a>
          page explains how.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="pp-section">
        <h2>The name</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>DAIODA</strong> comes from <em>Data / AI / In / Out</em>, and from the phonetic
          rhythm of "Day-O." The site's daybreak motif and its counted, call-and-response cadence are
          an original, transformative nod to the tradition of dockworkers' tally songs — a structural
          homage only. DAIODA is not affiliated with, endorsed by, or connected to any recording,
          performer, or rights holder, and reproduces no lyrics, music, or protected artwork.
        </p>
      </section>

      <div class="pp-cta">
        <a href="/about" class="btn btn-primary">About the experiment →</a>
        <a href="/projects" class="btn">Browse the catalog</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
  <style>
    .prose-page { padding-top: 3rem; }
    .pp-head { max-width: 62ch; }
    .pp-lede { font-size: 1.28rem; color: var(--ink-dim); line-height: 1.55; }
    .pp-lede strong { color: var(--ink); }
    .pp-section { max-width: 70ch; margin-top: 3.2rem; }
    .pp-section h2 { font-size: 1.8rem; margin-bottom: 0.8rem; }
    .pp-section p { color: var(--ink-dim); font-size: 1.06rem; line-height: 1.65; }
    .pp-section strong { color: var(--ink); }
    .pp-section em { color: var(--ink); font-style: italic; }
    .pp-section a { color: var(--accent); }
    .pp-section p a { border-bottom: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent) 35%, transparent); }
    .credit { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1.2rem 0; }
    .credit th, .credit td { text-align: left; padding: 0.7rem 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line); font-size: 0.98rem; vertical-align: top; }
    .credit th { width: 34%; font-weight: 600; }
    .credit td { color: var(--ink-dim); }
    .pp-cta { display: flex; gap: 0.8rem; margin-top: 3.5rem; flex-wrap: wrap; }
    @media (max-width: 620px) { .credit th { width: 42%; } }
  </style>
</Base>
